>shout it at work.
 
It was pretty shocking, at least in its sudden swiftness after dragging on
for all those months.  Personally I still think he did it, but I can't
really find fault with the jury for thinking there was a reasonable doubt.
The LAPD has been notorious for its racism for decades, so no matter how
overwhelming the physical and circumstantial evidence, it doesn't take a
Johnny Cochran to get a jury to distrust the people who are gathering this
evidence enough to come back with an acquittal.  It's pretty tragic that
this lesson has to come at the expense of two human lives and a lot of
anguish for several families, but if we're lucky, a few police departments
across the country may wake up and realize that, hey, keeping racist
officers on the force just might be a LIABILITY; having them involved tends
to create reasonable doubt in the minds of juries, and the DA's finding it
harder to get those convictions he needs so people will VOTE for him next
election!  Duh!
 
Everyone drop this suggestion to YOUR local precinct; let's see what happens...
 
Steve
